result.execSummary:
The defendant Quandella Rejoyce Johnson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Quandella Rejoyce Johnson is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Quandella Rejoyce Johnson was found guilty of Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).
  • Quandella Rejoyce Johnson was found guilty of Bail Jumping-Misdemeanor, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Quandella Rejoyce Johnson in court with attorney Anne M Jaspers.  Defendant Quandella Rejoyce Johnson in custody.  Sarra Mae Kiaie appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
cab
Parties are in court for a plea and sentencing.
As to counts 2 and 3:
  Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, and plead GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Stipulation by parties to complaint as a factual basis to sustain the plea.  Court found the defendant guilty. Judgment of conviction entered.
As to count 1:
On state's motion and pursuant to negotiations, court ordered count 1 dismissed and read-in for sentencing.
.
Sentencing continued...
.
As to count 2:
  Sentencing proceeds.    Upon inquiry of the Court, State advises they have complied with victim notification. Statements by counsel and defendant. 

COURT ORDERS defendant to serve 40 days  at the House of Correction with 40 days credit.  Time served disposition.
The court waived all costs and surcharges, finding the defendant indigent.

As to count 3:
Court sentenced the defendant to serve 8 months in the House of Correction, straight time,  with credit for -0- days served. 
 Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on probation for 18 months with the following conditions:
- Complete Parenting Classes.
- Mental health evaluation; take all prescribed medications.
- AODA assessment; comply with any treatment.
- Maintain absolute sobriety; random urine screens.
- Defendant not to use any corporal punishment on any child.
- Attend treatment and/or counseling as determined.
- No contact with her daughter unless approved through the bureau or Children's Court proceedings.  If the Bureau closes their case and the Children's Court matter, the defendant may have no violent contact if approved by the agent.
- No contact with firearms.
- The court found that the defendant is indigent and waived all costs and surcharges.
- Court set restitution at zero.
 
Received and filed:

Court advised defendant of penalties for violating the no contact order and due to this DV conviction s/he may never possess firearms or ammunition.
